title: 9News Adelaide | Sunday November 16  | Full Episode
description: Will McDonald and Alice Monfries lead the Adelaide news with a major safety scandal and dramatic rescues. The lead story details a terrifying product safety recall across South Australia, as hundreds of school classrooms and homes must be cleared of play sand that is feared to contain asbestos. We hear from officials and a worried parent as the cleaning operation begins. The bulletin also features a dramatic all-night standoff in the Adelaide CBD. A young man was successfully rescued by emergency services after climbing and sitting atop a towering crane for eight hours, forcing a major police operation and the closure of city streets. Internationally, parts of the UK, including Wales, are battling severe flooding caused by Storm Claudia, which also triggered a deadly tornado in Portugal. Other key stories covered include an update on the troubled disability provider Bedford, with the Premier hinting at a positive deal to save over 1,400 jobs. Federal politics is also in the spotlight as the Liberal-National Coalition unveils its new energy policy, replacing the net-zero goal with a commitment to nuclear energy and support for coal-fired plants. title: 9News Brisbane | Sunday November 16 | Full Episode
description: Mia Glover leads the Queensland news on a wild weather event, local crime, and a major political policy shift. The South East of the state was battered by extreme rain, causing flash flooding and chaos on the roads, including a dramatic incident where a car smashed through a homeowner's fence after spinning off a flooded street. Weather experts confirm there's little immediate reprieve, with continued storms and cool conditions expected. In crime news, a wanted man was dramatically arrested outside a Mermaid Beach Surf Club after allegedly carrying out two armed robberies on the Gold Coast. The tense police pursuit ended in the car park, where the man was pinned down. Internationally, the domestic dispute between Donald Trump and Marjorie Taylor Greene intensified, with the former President publicly branding her a "ranting lunatic" and withdrawing support over her push to release the Epstein files. The bulletin also covers a significant development in Federal politics: the Liberal-National Coalition has unveiled a new energy policy, abandoning the net-zero emissions target in favour of nuclear power and a potential return to coal-fired power station subsidies.
